    <!-- DETOX PROCESS -->
    <details class="card blue" id="detox-support">
      <summary>
        <h2>Supporting Your Body’s Detoxification Process</h2>
        <p>Your body already has powerful detox systems. Click to see how to mobilize, process, and eliminate toxins safely and efficiently.</p>
      </summary>
      <div class="collapse-body">
        <h3>1. Mobilizing Toxins from Tissues</h3>
        <p><strong>Healthy fat metabolism</strong> — many toxins are fat-soluble and stored in fat cells; gradual fat loss can release them for processing.</p>
        <p><strong>Herbs/nutrients that assist mobilization:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Brown laminaria seaweed</strong> — alginates bind certain metals/radioisotopes in the gut.</li>
          <li><strong>Zeolite</strong> — cage-like mineral binds metals and ammonium in the gut.</li>
          <li><strong>Sulfurzyme (MSM + NingXia wolfberry)</strong> — sulfur for sulfation; antioxidants to protect tissues during detox.</li>
          <li><strong>Green tea catechins</strong> — support fat metabolism and reduce oxidative stress.</li>
          <li><strong>Omega-3 fatty acids</strong> — improve membrane fluidity, help mobilize fat, and reduce inflammation.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. Processing Toxins in the Blood (Liver Phase I & II)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Phase I:</strong> Enzymes modify toxins to handle them.</li>
          <li><strong>Phase II:</strong> Conjugation (sulfur, glucuronic acid, glutathione, etc.) makes toxins water-soluble for elimination.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Key supports:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sulfur-rich foods</strong> (garlic, onions, crucifers, MSM) — feed sulfation pathways.</li>
          <li><strong>N-acetylcysteine (NAC)</strong> — glutathione precursor.</li>
          <li><strong>Milk thistle (silymarin)</strong> — supports hepatocyte integrity and antioxidant capacity.</li>
          <li><strong>Curcumin</strong> — reduces hepatic inflammation/oxidative stress.</li>
          <li><strong>Artichoke leaf extract</strong> — promotes bile flow; enzyme profile improvements.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3. Moving Toxins into the Gut (Bile & Lymph)</h3>
        <p><strong>Bile flow is essential</strong> — bile carries conjugated toxins into the intestines.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dandelion root</strong> — gentle choleretic.</li>
          <li><strong>Artichoke leaf extract</strong> — increases bile secretion.</li>
          <li><strong>Hydration & healthy fats</strong> — e.g., olive oil, avocado to stimulate bile release.</li>
          <li><strong>Manual lymphatic massage & movement</strong> — keeps lymph moving.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>4. Eliminating Toxins in Stool</h3>
        <p><strong>Regular bowel movements are non-negotiable</strong> — they prevent reabsorption (enterohepatic recirculation).</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Fiber</strong> (flax, chia, psyllium) — binds and speeds transit.</li>
          <li><strong>Short-term motility herbs</strong> — senna, cascara, aloe latex.</li>
          <li><strong>Probiotics</strong> — improve barrier integrity and reduce reabsorption.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>5. Eliminating Toxins in Urine</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Hydration</strong> — keep urine pale yellow.</li>
          <li><strong>Citrate-rich foods</strong> (lemon water) — help filtration & stone prevention.</li>
          <li><strong>Limit excess salt/processed foods</strong> — preserves kidney efficiency.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>6. Eliminating Toxins Through Skin & Lungs</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sweating</strong> — exercise, sauna, hot baths.</li>
          <li><strong>Deep breathing/fresh air</strong> — expels volatile compounds and CO₂.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Effective detox is a full-pathway approach—mobilize safely, process via the liver, move into gut/kidneys, then eliminate in stool, urine, sweat, and breath. Skipping a step lets toxins recirculate.</p>
        </div>
